---
import DocsNav from '../../components/DocsNav.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../../components/SiteFooter.astro';
import SiteNav from '../../components/SiteNav.astro';
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="CLI · neondeck"
  description="neondeck CLI commands for onboarding, status, repository management, watches, schedules, and future TUI entrypoints."
>
  <div class="site-shell">
    <SiteNav />
    <main class="container docs-layout">
      <DocsNav />
      <article class="docs-prose">
        <h1>CLI</h1>
        <p>
          The CLI is the setup and command-and-control surface for neondeck. It
          also reserves the future OpenTUI launch path so the terminal client
          can reuse the same backend runtime.
        </p>

        <h2>Global options</h2>
        <pre><code>npm run cli -- --home ~/.config/neondeck status
npm run cli -- --json status</code></pre>
        <p>
          Use <code>--home</code> to isolate a runtime home for testing. Use
          <code>--json</code> for machine-readable output where supported.
        </p>

        <h2>Initialize</h2>
        <pre><code>npm run init
npm run cli -- init --home .neondeck-test</code></pre>
        <p>
          The init wizard creates runtime files, writes runtime-home secrets,
          tunes <code>SOUL.md</code>, configures models and provider references,
          adds repositories, applies a dashboard preset, and can create initial
          schedules and command preapprovals.
        </p>

        <h2>Status</h2>
        <pre><code>npm run cli -- status</code></pre>
        <p>
          Status reports runtime readiness, active home paths, model/provider
          config, credential presence, repo counts, skills, watches, and setup
          items that need attention.
        </p>

        <h2>Database</h2>
        <pre><code>npm run cli -- db status
npm run cli -- --json db status</code></pre>
        <p>
          Database status reads the Neondeck app database migration journal,
          shipped migration head, pending entries, unknown newer entries, hash
          mismatches, and latest pre-migration backup path. There is no manual
          migrate command; migrations apply automatically before app code opens
          <code>data/neondeck.db</code>.
        </p>

        <h2>Repositories</h2>
        <pre><code>npm run cli -- repo add ~/dev/neondeck \
  --github-owner pandemicsyn \
  --github-name neondeck

npm run cli -- repo list</code></pre>
        <p>
          Repositories should be local git checkouts when you want local status,
          dev doctor diagnostics, and command execution against the repo.
        </p>

        <h2>Watches</h2>
        <pre><code>npm run cli -- watch-pr pandemicsyn/neondeck#521
npm run cli -- watch-pr pandemicsyn/neondeck#521 --until prod
npm run cli -- watch-pr https://github.com/pandemicsyn/neondeck/pull/521</code></pre>
        <p>
          PR watches persist in SQLite and poll GitHub for merge/check changes.
          <code>--until prod</code> links the source PR to a release watch after merge.
        </p>

        <h2>Schedules</h2>
        <pre><code>npm run cli -- schedule
npm run cli -- schedule --morning-briefing
npm run cli -- schedule --review-queue-digest</code></pre>
        <p>
          Natural-language scheduling is reserved for later. Today, the CLI
          creates known schedule blueprints and lists configured jobs.
        </p>

        <h2>MCP servers</h2>
        <pre><code>npm run cli -- mcp list
npm run cli -- mcp add linear --url https://mcp.linear.app/mcp --oauth
npm run cli -- mcp login linear
npm run cli -- mcp tools linear
npm run cli -- mcp approvals
npm run cli -- mcp approvals --resolve &lt;id&gt; --approve
npm run cli -- mcp logout linear --confirm</code></pre>
        <p>
          MCP config lives in runtime-home <code>mcp.json</code>. Stdio servers,
          header-authenticated servers, and auto-approval policy should be
          managed from user-owned CLI, local API, or config surfaces.
        </p>

        <h2>Learning</h2>
        <pre><code>npm run cli -- learning status
npm run cli -- learning reviews
npm run cli -- learning candidates --status proposed
npm run cli -- learning approve &lt;candidate-id&gt;
npm run cli -- learning reject &lt;candidate-id&gt;
npm run cli -- learning restore-skill-patch &lt;candidate-id&gt;</code></pre>
        <p>
          Learning commands inspect the same review, candidate, and audit state
          as <code>GET /api/learning/state</code>. Approve/reject commands
          decide memory or skill candidates through typed actions. Restore only
          works for applied skill patches whose current file still matches the
          applied audit hash.
        </p>

        <h2>TUI</h2>
        <pre><code>npm run cli -- tui</code></pre>
        <p>
          The command is reserved for the future OpenTUI client. The TUI should
          reuse backend APIs and event streams rather than growing a second
          agent runtime.
        </p>
      </article>
    </main>
    <SiteFooter />
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
